How would you design a highly available system on AWS?

To design a highly available system on AWS, I would deploy resources across multiple Availability Zones using Elastic Load Balancing and Auto Scaling to handle instance failures. To handle regional failures, I’d use Route 53 with health checks and failover routing to redirect traffic to a secondary region. This ensures no single point of failure across infrastructure layers.


What is the best way to implement a fault-tolerant, multi-region AWS architecture with EC2 instances in Auto Scaling Groups behind Application Load Balancers, and use Route 53 routing policies to handle regional failover?

Yes—you absolutely can:

✔ 2 EC2 instances per region in ASG
✔ Load balancer per region
✔ Route 53 for routing & failover
✔ Multi-region resilience

🏗️ How RDS Fits Into Your Architecture

Now your full setup becomes:

Region A (Primary)
ALB → ASG → EC2
RDS (Primary DB)
Region B (Secondary)
ALB → ASG → EC2
RDS (Replica / Secondary DB)
Global Layer
Route 53 → directs traffic

What happens to the data when we change the instance type of an EC2 instance? Are there any scenarios where data loss can occur?

Changing from t2.micro → t2.large does NOT cause data loss as long as:

You didn’t terminate the instance
You’re using EBS (default)
